n\n#### Options\n- `--sessions` - Clean old sessions\n- `--logs` - Clean old logs\n- `--cache` - Clean cached data\n- `--all` - Clean everything\n- `--older-than <duration>` - Only clean files older than duration\n- `--dry-run` - Show what would be deleted without deleting\n- `--force` - Skip confirmation prompts\n\n#### Use Cases\n- Free disk space\n- Remove stale data\n- Maintenance automation\n- Privacy cleanup\n\n#### Output Format\n```\nCodeMie Cleanup\n\nAnalyzing...\n\nFound:\n  • 45 sessions (124 MB)\n  • 12 log files (8 MB)\n  • 3 cache entries (2 MB)\n\nTotal: 134 MB can be freed\n\nWhat to clean?\n❯ ◉ Sessions older than 30 days (32 files, 98 MB)\n  ◉ Log files older than 7 days (8 files, 5 MB)\n  ◯ All cache (2 MB)\n\n✓ Cleaned 106 MB\n  • Removed 40 old files\n  • Kept 8 recent sessions\n\nRun 'codemie clean --all' to remove everything\n```\n\n#### Implementation Approach\n1. Scan session directories for old files\n2. Calculate sizes and counts\n3. Interactive selection or use flags\n4. Confirm before deletion (unless `--force`)\n5. Delete files and report results\n\n**Factory Function:** `createCleanCommand()`\n**Location:** `src/cli/commands/clean.ts`\n**Utilities:** Use `SessionStore`, file system utils\n\n---\n\n### 9. `codemie login` / `codemie logout` - Authentication\n\n**Priority:** LOW\n**Category:** Authentication\n\n#### Purpose\nSimplified authentication commands. Wrappers around `profile auth` with better UX.\n\n#### Syntax\n```bash\ncodemie login\ncodemie login --profile <name>\ncodemie logout\ncodemie logout --all\n```\n\n#### Options\n- `--profile <name>` - Login to specific profile\n- `--all` - Logout from all profiles (logout only)\n\n#### Use Cases\n- Quick authentication flow\n- Team onboarding\n- Familiar command names (like docker, npm)\n- SSO authentication\n\n#### Output Format\n```bash\n$ codemie login\nAuthenticating with SSO...\n\n✓ Authentication successful\n✓ Logged in as: john@company.com\n✓ Access token saved to profile: sso\n\nReady to use CodeMie!\n\n$ codemie logout\n✓ Logged out from profile: sso\n```\n\n#### Implementation Approach\n1. `login` → wrapper around `profile auth login`\n2. `logout` → wrapper around `profile auth logout`\n3. Add convenient defaults and better messaging\n4. Support SSO and API key authentication\n5. Integrate with existing auth infrastructure\n\n**Factory Function:** `createLoginCommand()`, `createLogoutCommand()`\n**Location:** `src/cli/commands/login.ts`, `src/cli/commands/logout.ts`\n**Pattern:** Delegate to existing profile auth logic\n\n---\n\n### 10. `codemie inspect` - Deep Inspection\n\n**Priority:** LOW\n**Category:** Diagnostics\n\n#### Purpose\nDeep inspection tool for troubleshooting. View session details, metrics, configuration, and system info.\n\n#### Syntax\n```bash\ncodemie inspect\ncodemie inspect session <id>\ncodemie inspect config\ncodemie inspect system\n```\n\n#### Subcommands\n- `(default)` - Overall system inspection\n- `session <id>` - Deep dive into session\n- `config` - Configuration validation\n- `system` - System environment details\n\n#### Options\n- `--json` - Output as JSON\n- `--verbose` - Show all details\n\n#### Use Cases\n- Advanced troubleshooting\n- Bug report generation\n- Configuration validation\n- System diagnostics\n\n#### Output Format\n```\nCodeMie System Inspection\n\nEnvironment:\n  Node.js:        v24.0.0\n  OS:             macOS 14.6.0 (arm64)\n  CodeMie:        v0.0.18\n  Working Dir:    /Users/dev/myapp\n\nConfiguration:\n  Global Config:  ~/.codemie/config.json (valid ✓)\n  Project Config: .codemie/config.json (valid ✓)\n  Active Profile: default\n\nProfiles:\n  • default (openai) - active\n  • work (bedrock) - valid\n  • personal (ollama) - ⚠ model not installed\n\nAgents:\n  • claude-code: v0.0.18 (installed ✓)\n  • codex: v1.2.3 (installed ✓)\n  • gemini-cli: v0.1.5 (installed ✓)\n\nStorage:\n  Sessions:       ~/.codemie/sessions/ (45 files, 124 MB)\n  Logs:           ~/.codemie/logs/codemie.log (8 MB)\n  Cache:          ~/.codemie/cache/ (2 MB)\n\nHealth Checks:\n  ✓ All systems operational\n```\n\n#### Implementation Approach\n1. Gather system information (Node.js, OS, versions)\n2. Validate all configurations\n3. Check agent installations\n4. Analyze storage usage\n5. Run health checks\n6. Format comprehensive report\n\n**Factory Function:** `createInspectCommand()`\n**Location:** `src/cli/commands/inspect.ts`\n**Utilities:** Reuse `doctor` checks, `ConfigLoader`, `AgentRegistry`\n\n---\n\n## Priority Matrix\n\n| Command | Priority | Complexity | Impact | Effort |\n|---------|----------|------------|--------|--------|\n| `init` | HIGH | Low | High | 1-2 days |\n| `status` | HIGH | Low | High | 1-2 days |\n| `config` | MEDIUM | Medium | Medium | 2-3 days |\n| `history` | MEDIUM | Medium | Medium | 2-3 days |\n| `test` | MEDIUM | Low | Medium | 1 day |\n| `exec` | MEDIUM | Medium | High | 2-3 days |\n| `logs` | LOW | Low | Low | 1 day |\n| `clean` | LOW | Medium | Low | 2 days |\n| `login/logout` | LOW | Low | Low | 1 day |\n| `inspect` | LOW | Medium | Low | 2-3 days |\n\n**Total Effort:** 15-23 developer days\n\n---\n\n## Implementation Plan\n\n### Phase 1: Core Commands (High Priority)\n1. `codemie init` - Project initialization\n2. `codemie status` - Quick status overview\n\n**Duration:** 2-4 days\n**Value:** Immediate UX improvement\n\n### Phase 2: Configuration & Testing (Medium Priority)\n3. `codemie config` - Configuration management\n4. `codemie test` - Connectivity testing\n5. `codemie exec` - One-off execution\n\n**Duration:** 5-9 days\n**Value:** Power user features, scripting support\n\n### Phase 3: History & Utilities (Medium-Low Priority)\n6. `codemie history` - Session history\n7. `codemie logs` - Log viewing\n8. `codemie clean` - Cleanup maintenance\n\n**Duration:** 4-6 days\n**Value:** Maintenance and troubleshooting\n\n### Phase 4: Authentication & Diagnostics (Low Priority)\n9. `codemie login/logout` - Auth shortcuts\n10. `codemie inspect` - Deep inspection\n\n**Duration:** 3-4 days\n**Value:** Polish and advanced diagnostics\n\n---\n\n## Shared Implementation Patterns\n\n### 1. Factory Pattern\nAll commands follow the same factory pattern:\n\n```typescript\nexport function createCommandName(): Command {\n  return new Command('command-name')\n    .description('Command description')\n    .option('-o, --option', 'Option description')\n    .action(async (options) => {\n      // Implementation\n    });\n}\n```\n\n### 2. Error Handling\nConsistent error handling across all commands:\n\n```typescript\n.action(async (options) => {\n  try {\n    // Command logic\n  } catch (error) {\n    logger.error('Command failed:', error);\n    console.error(chalk.red(`✗ ${error.message}`));\n    process.exit(1);\n  }\n});\n```\n\n### 3. User Feedback\nUse consistent UI components:\n- `ora` for spinners\n- `chalk` for colors\n- `@clack/prompts` for interactive inputs\n- Table formatting for lists\n\n### 4. Configuration Access\nReuse existing utilities:\n- `ConfigLoader` for all config operations\n- `AgentRegistry` for agent information\n- `SessionStore` for session data\n- `MetricsDataLoader` for analytics\n\n### 5. Testing\nIntegration tests for all commands:\n\n```typescript\ndescribe('command-name', () => {\n  it('should display help', async () => {\n    const { stdout } = await execAsync('codemie command-name --help');\n    expect(stdout).toContain('Command description');\n  });\n\n  it('should handle errors gracefully', async () => {\n    // Test error scenarios\n  });\n});\n```\n\n---\n\n## Architecture Considerations\n\n### Dependencies\nNo new external dependencies required. All commands use existing utilities:\n- Commander.js (already used)\n- Chalk (already used)\n- Ora (already used)\n- @clack/prompts (already used)\n- Inquirer (already used)\n\n### Backward Compatibility\nAll new commands are additive. No breaking changes to existing commands.\n\n### Cross-Platform Support\nAll commands must work on Windows, macOS, and Linux:\n- Use Node.js `path` module for paths\n- Use cross-platform file operations\n- Test on all platforms\n\n### Configuration Hierarchy\nAll commands respect existing hierarchy:\n1. CLI arguments (highest)\n2. Environment variables\n3. Project config (.codemie/)\n4. Global config (~/.codemie/)\n5. Defaults (lowest)\n\n---\n\n## Testing Strategy\n\n### Unit Tests\n- Test command factory functions\n- Test option parsing\n- Test validation logic\n\n### Integration Tests\n- Test full command execution\n- Test with different configurations\n- Test error scenarios\n\n### Manual Testing\n- Test on all platforms (Windows, macOS, Linux)\n- Test with different providers\n- Test edge cases\n\n---\n\n## Documentation Updates\n\n### User Documentation\nUpdate `docs/COMMANDS.md` with:\n- New command descriptions\n- Usage examples\n- Options and flags\n\n### Developer Documentation\nUpdate `src/cli/CLAUDE.md` with:\n- Implementation patterns\n- Reference examples\n- Testing guidelines\n\n### README\nUpdate main README with:\n- New commands in feature list\n- Updated command list section\n\n---\n\n## Success Metrics\n\n### User Experience\n- Reduced time to first value\n- Fewer support questions about configuration\n- Increased power user adoption\n\n### Code Quality\n- All tests passing\n- Zero ESLint warnings\n- Full TypeScript coverage\n\n### Adoption\n- Command usage tracked in analytics\n- User feedback collection\n- Community feedback incorporation\n\n---\n\n## Risks and Mitigations\n\n### Risk: Command Naming Conflicts\n**Mitigation:** Research existing CLI tools, avoid common names, allow aliases\n\n### Risk: Configuration Complexity\n**Mitigation:** Keep commands simple, provide good defaults, clear documentation\n\n### Risk: Cross-Platform Issues\n**Mitigation:** Test on all platforms, use Node.js path utilities, avoid shell-specific features\n\n### Risk: Maintenance Burden\n**Mitigation:** Follow DRY principles, reuse existing utilities, comprehensive tests\n\n---\n\n## Open Questions\n\n1. Should `codemie exec` support multiple agents in sequence?\n2. Should `codemie history` support session replay?\n3. Should `codemie clean` have automatic cleanup policies?\n4. Should `codemie test` support performance benchmarking?\n5. Should `codemie config` support config templates?\n\n**Resolution:** Address during implementation based on user feedback.\n\n---\n\n## Appendix: CLI Best Practices Reference\n\n### Command Design\n- **Single responsibility** - Each command does one thing well\n- **Composability** - Commands can be chained and scripted\n- **Discoverability** - Clear help text and examples\n- **Consistency** - Similar commands work similarly\n\n### Option Design\n- **Short and long forms** - `-v` and `--verbose`\n- **Sensible defaults** - Work without options where possible\n- **Boolean flags** - No `--no-` unless necessary\n- **Validation** - Fail fast with clear errors\n\n### Output Design\n- **Human-readable** - Clear formatting with colors\n- **Machine-readable** - `--json` option where appropriate\n- **Progressive disclosure** - Details on demand with `--verbose`\n- **Exit codes** - 0 for success, non-zero for errors\n\n### Documentation\n- **Help text** - Concise but complete\n- **Examples** - Show common use cases\n- **Man pages** - For complex commands\n- **Online docs** - Reference documentation\n\n---\n\n## References\n\n- [Commander.js Documentation](https://github.com/tj/commander.js)\n- [CLI Guidelines](https://clig.dev/)\n- [12 Factor CLI Apps](https://medium.com/@jdxcode/12-factor-cli-apps-dd3c227a0e46)\n- [POSIX Utility Conventions](https://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/basedefs/V1_chap12.html)\n\n---\n\n**END OF SPECIFICATION**\n","structuredPatch":[],"originalFile":null},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"a98d6722-a41d-43e3-a88c-74ce467a9d30"}
